 $1,000/year you’re looking at JazzHR’s Hero tier, which is the “hiring essentials” package built for small teams with a few open roles at a time.

Core pricing mechanics
List pricing: Hero is marketed around $75–$110/month when billed annually (JazzHR’s own pages show $1,000/year with “save up to 24% by paying yearly”).

Active jobs: Includes 3 active/open jobs; additional open‑job slots can be added for $9 per job per month.

Intended size: Described as ideal for small businesses or startups with basic hiring needs and only a few simultaneous openings.

Staffing‑firm pricing can be higher (some docs mention $99+/month), but that doesn’t apply if this is an in‑house employer, not an agency.

Given your 3–5 concurrent roles, you’d probably sit at 3 included jobs most of the time and occasionally pay for 1–2 extra slots when you spike.

What features Hero actually includes
Across JazzHR docs and pricing breakdowns, Hero consistently includes the “core ATS” set; here’s what you can count on.

Job posting & syndication

Post a job once in JazzHR and push it to multiple free job boards (Indeed, Glassdoor, etc.) and social media.

Promote on premium job boards (paid slots) via JazzHR if you choose.

Applicant tracking (pipeline)

Custom workflow stages (e.g., New → Phone Screen → Weld Test → Onsite → Offer → Hired).

Kanban/pipeline views with drag‑and‑drop movement of candidates between stages.

Candidate profiles with resume storage, activity history, and internal notes.

Candidate communications

Email message templates you can reuse for acknowledgements, rejection, and next‑steps emails.

Email sync so replies and outreach can be tracked in JazzHR instead of scattered across inboxes.

Candidate email alerts and notifications.
​

Sourcing & branding basics

Branded career page options and the ability to embed JazzHR jobs into your website.

Easy social‑sharing tools to push jobs to LinkedIn and other networks.
​

LinkedIn Recruiter integration listed as part of the Hero package.

Collaboration & admin

At least one main user; some sources say Hero is single‑user while others list “unlimited users,” but all agree that Plus/Pro add more collaboration controls, custom roles, and advanced workflows.

Basic document storage (resumes, offer docs, attachments).
​

In short: Hero gives you a full functioning ATS with posting, pipeline, email templates, and simple reporting, not a “lite toy” version.

What Hero does not include (vs Plus)
The Hero tier omits several high‑end features that are only in Plus/Pro.

No AI‑powered candidate matching: that’s explicitly listed only on Plus and up.
​

No advanced task automation or complex workflow automations (e.g., heavy conditional rules or bulk automations) beyond the basics.

More limited reporting: Plus/Pro add more comprehensive or “standard” reporting suites; Hero has basic metrics but not deep analytics and visual dashboards.

No e‑signatures/offers or advanced visual reporting, which are Pro‑level features.

Lower active‑job ceiling (3 plus $9/job add‑ons) vs 200 active jobs in Plus.

For your case—three steady roles and occasional spikes—the missing high‑volume features are less critical; the biggest tradeoff is giving up AI matching and some automation/analytics.

How Hero will actually feel for your welders/engineering hiring
For a welding‑heavy shop with a couple of higher‑level roles, Hero is designed to remove the admin grind even without the fancier AI.

Posting flow:

You create three templates (Welder, Welding Inspector, Head of Engineering) in JazzHR and publish once; they syndicate to free boards like Indeed and to your website career page.

Screening & pipelines:

Add required application questions (years of welding experience, certifications, shift, pay range acceptance), then use those answers to quickly filter and move candidates.

Set up a weld‑test stage and a technical interview stage so hiring managers see exactly where each candidate sits.
​

Communication:

Auto‑send “we got your application” messages and use templates for rejections so managers aren’t typing the same emails repeatedly.

Management time savings:

Centralizing resumes and communication can cut each manager from juggling email/Excel to spending focused time in one dashboard, which is where most Hero‑plan ROI comes from.

Is Hero the right call for ST?
Given everything above and your 3–5‑role reality:

Cost fit: Hero’s $1,000/year pricing with 3 job slots matches your expected volume almost perfectly; you may occasionally add a $9/month slot during a surge.

Capability fit: It covers all the essentials—posting to Indeed, tracking candidates, templates, and basic reporting—without paying a 3.5x premium for Plus.

AI tradeoff: Because public reviews don’t treat JazzHR’s AI matching as transformational and your volume isn’t huge, it’s unlikely that feature alone will generate $2,480/year of extra value in saved time.

If ST later finds themselves with many more open roles or drowning in applicants, they can upgrade to Plus for AI matching and deeper automation, but the smart move now is to start on Hero, dial in good screening questions and workflows, and keep the spend tight.
